  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termSlug": "resist"
                }
              }
            ],
            "text": "resist"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " decoration reverses the normal painting process: instead of applying colour to the areas you want to be coloured, you apply wax to the areas you want to remain their original colour. The wash then covers everything, but the waxed areas repel it. The result is the original clay or base colour showing as the pattern against a washed background."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When to use this technique"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Apply wax resist to pieces that are fully "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termSlug": "bone-dry"
                }
              }
            ],
            "text": "bone-dry"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ". Wet clay will absorb the wax before it can act as a surface resist. Use wax resist before applying any slip or diluted paint wash; it does not work under acrylic paint applied at full thickness."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "What you need"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Bone-dry air-dry clay piece"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Wax emulsion (pottery wax resist or clear water-based batik wax)"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Liner brush for fine pattern work"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Mop brush for the wash application"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Coloured slip diluted to wash consistency, or acrylic paint diluted 1:3 with water"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Step by step"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Plan the pattern. Simple geometric shapes, spot patterns, or simple botanical outlines work well. The waxed areas will remain the base colour; the unwaxed areas will take the wash colour."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Dip the liner brush in wax emulsion and apply it to the areas of the piece that you want to keep as the base colour. The wax is milky-white when wet; it dries to a slightly shiny translucent film. Apply a generous coat; thin wax will not fully resist the wash."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Leave the wax to dry for 20 minutes. Check coverage: any gaps in the waxed pattern will take the colour."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Apply the coloured wash broadly over the entire surface with the mop brush in a single pass. Do not overbrush; the wax resists better when not scrubbed."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Allow to dry. The waxed areas will show the wash beading off and leaving the base clay colour; the unwaxed areas will take the wash evenly."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "The wax remains on the surface under the varnish. Seal with two coats of PVA varnish once the wash is fully dry."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "What it looks like when it is right"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The waxed pattern should read as a clean two-tone design. The waxed areas show the original clay colour cleanly with no wash colour penetrating. The edges between waxed and unwaxed areas are sharp. A clean brush edge when applying wax gives a sharper resist line."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Common mistakes"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Applying wax to wet or damp clay. The clay absorbs the wax instead of having it sit on the surface."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Using too thin a wax coat; the wash bleeds through thin patches."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Scrubbing the wash over waxed areas. Apply in one gentle pass to keep the resist clean."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
}